      <p>Summary of important ideas regarding applying the limit definition of the derivative
      </p>

      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              When applying the limit definition of the derivative, it's essential to correctly apply the rule for the function <m>f(x)</m> to compute <m>f(a+h)</m> for the relevant value of <m>a</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For some nice functions, algebra can be used to simplify the difference quotient, <m>\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}</m>, to find a factor of <m>h</m> in the numerator.  Then the factor of <m>h</m> in the numerator and denominator divide to result in <m>1</m>.  From there, with no <m>h</m> in the denominator, letting <m>h \to 0</m> produces the value of <m>f'(a)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              For other functions, it's not possible to remove a factor of <m>h</m> from the numerator of the difference quotient, so it may be necessary to estimate <m>\frac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}</m> using small values of <m>h</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

